transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Thank you for calling Viagra. How can I assist you?

Speaker 2: Hi. How are you?

Speaker 1: I'm well. How are you doing today?

Speaker 2: Good. So I had an order last month and I already received it.

Speaker 1: Then this week I found that my card got recharged again for $115.

Speaker 2: And I didn't order any refills or I didn't even apply for auto refills.

Speaker 1: So can we please fix this and get a refund?

Speaker 2: If I can further assist you, if I can have your name and your date of birth

Speaker 1: so I can pull your account up.

Speaker 2: Sure. My name is Hany and my date of birth is 11-27-67.

Speaker 1: Great.

Speaker 2: Okay, Hany, it looks like the prescription that you currently have that Dr. Tariq wrote,

Speaker 1: it does come with refills for every two months.

Speaker 2: It does say on your bottle, it will say how many refills you have left.

Speaker 1: So that's why you were charged for another refill and you actually have one on the way to you.

Speaker 2: No, I want to cancel it. I want to cancel it.

Speaker 1: I will do refills when I need it, not just an auto refill.

Speaker 2: So how our programs work is that the prescription does come with refills.

Speaker 1: You're not obligated to get it every two months.

Speaker 2: If it is something that you know that you're going to want to continue to get down the line,

Speaker 1: what we could do is adjust it to every six months so that way your prescription is active.

Speaker 2: No, you adjust it to get the refill when it's ordered, not every two months, not every six months.

Speaker 1: I don't want to manage an account like this.

Speaker 2: So whenever I need it, I'm going to just set an order. It's simple.

Speaker 1: Okay, I understand that, but I'm trying to explain to you that's not how our program works.

Speaker 2: So if you want to cancel your refills, I can do that.

Speaker 1: Just know that you won't be able to – you'll be put on a wait list to reorder

Speaker 2: and you'll have to pay for the doctor's prescription the next time around.

Speaker 1: Sure.

Speaker 2: Okay, so I'll go ahead and cancel it.

Speaker 1: Yes, please.

Speaker 2: All right, and you're all set.

Speaker 1: And how long does it take for a refund?

Speaker 2: Well, the order was shipped to you, so if you don't want that order,

Speaker 1: I'm showing it's going to be delivered on Monday.

Speaker 2: So you can refuse it, and then once it's received, your card on file will be refunded.

Speaker 1: I'm going to be traveling, and there is a storm here.

Speaker 2: I can't believe this is happening now.

Speaker 1: Even if it's every two months, is that two months?

Speaker 2: Two months has already passed?

Speaker 1: Yeah, you got it in November.

Speaker 2: So now when I get this shipment, are you sure it already got shipped?

Speaker 1: Yeah, I have a tracking number on it, and it shows that it was going to be delivered on Monday.

Speaker 2: It's currently in Jersey City.

Speaker 1: Okay, so what are the steps in order to ship it back?

Speaker 2: So when you collect it, just from your mailbox, don't open it.

Speaker 1: Write refuse, return to sender, and just put it back in your mailbox for the mailman to collect.

Speaker 2: No, say that again, please.

Speaker 1: So I'm going to not open the thing, but that's obvious.

Speaker 2: And then?

Speaker 1: Write refuse, return to sender, and put it back in the mailbox for the mailman to collect.

Speaker 2: Okay, and usually how long does it take?

Speaker 1: It usually takes about a week for it to go back, or a few days for it to go back to the pharmacy.

Speaker 2: And once they receive it, it takes like three days for it to process, the refund to process.

Speaker 1: All right, okay. Thank you very much.

Speaker 2: You're welcome. Have a good day.
